 winning - Tracy cheated her way to the trophy last year and there's no way that's happening again. Angelo's got an aerodynamic bed, a super-trained bed-pusher, he's got intel on his competition and a secret ally on the course - This year, anything goes.\n|LineColor=FF5C7D\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber = 51\n|EpisodeNumber2 = 25\n|Title = Brain Scrambler\n|WrittenBy = Andy Rheingold\n|OriginalAirDate = \n|ShortSummary = Angelo and friends celebrate the end of school at Adventureparkland and ride the brand new Brainscrambler roller coaster dozens of times which causes them to lose their memory of party. The three spend the rest of the day trying to desperately figure out why Sherwood has a beard, who Lola kissed, and where Angelo's dad's video camera had gone.\n|LineColor=FF5C7D\n}}\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber = 52\n|EpisodeNumber2 = 26\n|Title = The Candy Vault\n|WrittenBy = \n|OriginalAirDate = \n|ShortSummary = When Angelo finds out about a giant candy vault located under the school that holds every piece of candy that has ever been confiscated, he and the gang set out to pull off the greatest candy heist of all time and take back what's theirs.\n|LineColor=FF5C7D\n}}\n}}\n\n===Season 3===\n{{Episode table |background=BB9A8F |overall= |season= |title= |writer= |airdate= |episodes=\n{{Episode list\n|EpisodeNumber = 53\n|EpisodeNumber2 = 1\n|Title = Space Cadet/The Cheating Kind\n|WrittenBy =\n|OriginalAirDate = {{Start date|2016|}}\n|ShortSummary = '''Space Cadet:''' Angelo and Lola help Sherwood get into Space Camp by making an elaborate video of Sherwood as an astronaut with the Right Stuff.<br/>'''The Cheating Kind:''' Angelo tries a variety of strategies in an effort to cure Tracy of her obsession with cheating on anything, anywhere, anytime.\n|LineColor = BB9A8F\n}}\n}}\n\n==Broadcast==\n''Angelo Rules'' airs on [[Cartoon Network]] in over 152 countries. In the United States, the series was acquired by Cartoon Network and premiered on 1 January 2010, and the season two debuted on 2 June 2014.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.cartoonnetwork.com/tv_shows/angelo-rules/video/index.html?atclk_gn=picker_Angelo_Rules | title=Angelo Rules | publisher=Cartoon Network | accessdate=25 July 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2014/03/cartoon-network-unveils-upfront-slate-for-2014-15-696377/|title=Cartoon Network Unveils Upfront Slate For 2014-15|author=The Deadline Team|date=10 March 2014|work=Deadline Hollywood|publisher=PMC|accessdate=20 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\n''Angelo Rules'' was one of 24 nominees for the second International Emmy Kids Awards in 2013.<ref name=iatas>[http://www.iemmys.tv/news_item.aspx?id=169 International Emmy Kids Awards nominees announced] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131016075824/http://www.iemmys.tv/news_item.aspx?id=169 |date=2013-10-16 }}. International Academy of Television Arts & Sciences.  Accessed April 2014.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|tt1616209}}\n\n[[Category:2009 French television series debuts]]\n[[Category:France T\u00e9l\u00e9visions shows]]\n[[Category:French children's animated action television series]]\n[[Category:French children's animated adventure television series]]\n[[Category:French children's animated comedy television series]]\n[[Category:French children's animated fantasy television series]]\n[[Category:2000s French animated television series]]\n[[Category:French computer-animated television series]]\n[[Category:French television programs based on children's books]]\n[[Category:Animated television series about children]]\n\n{{Europe-tv-prog-stub}}\n", "name_user": "2a02:2e02:2d9a:8600:848b:505:70df:4966", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Angelo_Rules"}
{"title_page": "Shivakumara Swami", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian saint}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Shivakumara Swami\n|image              = Shivakumara Swami.png\n|caption            = Shivakumara Swami in June 2007, aged 100\n|birth_name         = Shivanna\n|birth_date         = {{birth date|1907|4|1|df=y}}\n|birth_place        = Veerapura, [[Magadi]], [[Kingdom of Mysore]]<ref name=indianexpress-20190121>{{cite web |title=Who was Shivakumara Swami? |url=https://indianexpress.com/article/who-is/shivakumara-swami-lingayat-siddhaganga-mutt-tumakuru-5548096/ |website=The Indian Express |accessdate=21 January 2019 |language=en-IN |date=21 January 2019}}</ref>\n|death_date         = {{death date|2019|1|21|df=y}}<br />(aged {{age in years and days|1907|4|1|2019|1|21}})<ref name=\"Hindu_passes\" />\n|death_place        = [[Tumkur]], Karnataka, India\n|other_names        = [[Siddaganga]] Swamigalu, Nadedaduva Devaru, Kayaka Yogi, Trivida Daasohi, Abhinava Basavanna<ref name=\"firstpost21\" />\n|organization       = Siddaganga Education Society\n|education          = [[Doctor of Literature]] (honourary, 1965)\n|occupation         = {{hlist|Humanitarian|spiritual leader|educator|head of [[Siddaganga Matha]]}}\n|awards             = [[Padma Bhushan]] (2015)<ref name=\"Hindu_passes\" /><br />[[Karnataka Ratna]] (2007)<ref name=\"TNIE_110\" />\n|years_active       = 1930\u20132019\n}}\n\n'''Shivakumara Swami''' (born '''Shivanna'''; 1 April 1907 \u2013 21 January 2019) was an Indian [[supercentenarian]], humanitarian, spiritual leader and educator. He was a [[Lingayatism|Lingayat]] religious figure, he joined the [[Siddaganga Matha]] in 1930 [[Karnataka]] and became head seer from 1941.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sreesiddagangamutt.org/|title=Sree Siddaganga Mutt|website=Sreesiddagangamutt.org|accessdate=31 January 2018}}</ref> He also founded the Sri Siddaganga Education Society.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sit.ac.in|title=Siddaganga Institute of Technology|website=Sit.ac.in|accessdate=25 September 2009}}</ref> Described as the most esteemed adherent of [[Lingayatism]],<ref name=\"veconomist\">{{cite news|title=A medieval poet bedevils India's most powerful political party|url=https://www.economist.com/news/asia/21729449-did-he-found-faith-or-just-faction-medieval-poet-bedevils-indias-most-powerful-political|work=[[The Economist]]|date=21 September 2017}}</ref> he was referred to as ''Nadedaaduva Devaru'' (walking God) in the state.<ref name=\"Hindu_passes\" />\n\nBefore his death at the age of 111 years, 295 days, he was one of the oldest people [[India#Demographics|living in India]].<ref name=\"oldest_IT\">{{cite news |title=Lingayat seer Shivakumara Swami dies at 111, Karnataka declares 3-day state mourning |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/shivakumara-swami-dead-1435579-2019-01-21 |accessdate=21 January 2019 |publisher=India Today |date=21 January 2019 |language=en}}</ref> In 2015, he was awarded by the Government of India the [[Padma Bhushan]], India's third highest civilian award.<ref name=\"Hindu_passes\"/>\n\n==Early life==\nShivanna was born on 1 April 1907 in Veerapura, a village near [[Magadi]] in the erstwhile [[Kingdom of Mysore]] (in present-day [[Ramanagara district]] of [[Karnataka]] state). He was the youngest of thirteen children of Gangamma and Honne Gowda. Having been devoted followers of the deities Gangadhareshwara and Honnadevi, Shivanna's parents took him to the shrines in [[Shivagange]], alongside other religious centres around Veerapura.<ref>{{cite web |title=Childhood |url=http://www.siddagangamath.org/siddaganga/childhood.html |website=siddagangamath.org |accessdate=21 January 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190121135201/http://www.siddagangamath.org/siddaganga/childhood.html |archivedate=21 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Sri Shivakumara Swami: A proud Veerapura says adieu to its famous son |url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/states/karnataka/2019/jan/22/a-proud-veerapura-says-adieu-to-its-famous-son-1928296.html |website=The New Indian Express |accessdate=22 January 2019 |date=22 January 2019}}</ref> His mother Gangamma died when he was eight.<ref>{{cite news |title=Prominent Lingayat seer Shivakumara Swami dies at 111 |url=https://www.rediff.com/news/report/prominent-lingayat-seer-shivakumara-swami-dies-at-111/20190121.htm |accessdate=21 January 2019 |work=Rediff.com |date=21 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nShivanna completed his elementary education in a rural anglo-vernacular school in Nagavalli, a village in the present-day [[Tumkur district]]. He passed his matriculation in 1926. He was also a resident-student at the Siddaganga Math for a brief span during this time. He enrolled in [[Central College of Bangalore]] to study in arts with physics and mathematics as optional subjects,<ref>{{cite web |title=Education |url=http://www.siddagangamath.org/siddaganga/education.html |website=siddagangamath.org |accessdate=21 January 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180404103201/http://www.siddagangamath.org/siddaganga/education.html |archivedate=21 January 2019}}</ref> but was unable to earn the bachelor's degree as he was named successor of Uddana Shivayogi Swami to head the [[Siddaganga Matha]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bhuvaneshwari |first1=S. |title=Shivakumara Swami: the 'Walking God' who left no one behind |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/karnataka/shivakumara-swami-the-walking-god-who-left-no-one-behind/article26054420.ece |newspaper=The Hindu |accessdate=22 January 2019 |language=en-IN |date=21 January 2019}}</ref> Shivanna was proficient in [[Kannada]], [[Sanskrit]] and English languages.<ref name=\"TheWeek21Jan\">{{cite news |title=Shivakumara Swamiji: 'Walking god' who believed in the power of education |url=https://www.theweek.in/news/india/2019/01/21/shivakumara-swamiji-walking-god-believed0-power-education.html |accessdate=21 January 2019 |publisher=The Week |date=21 January 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nAfter losing his friend and the heir to head the Siddaganga Matha, Sri Marularadhya, in January 1930, Shivanna was chosen in his place by the incumbent chief Shivayogi Swami. Shivanna, then renamed Shivakumara, entered the ''viraktashram'' (the monks' order) on 3 March that year upon formal initiation, and assumed the pontifical name Shivakumara Swami.<ref>{{cite web |title=Shivanna to Sree Sivakumara Swamigalu |url=http://www.siddagangamath.org/siddaganga/destination.html |website=siddagangamath.org |accessdate=21 January 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190121135613/http://www.siddagangamath.org/siddaganga/destination.html |archivedate=21 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=B. R. |first1=Rohith |title=Shivakumara Swamiji, 'walking god' of Karnataka, passes away |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/bengaluru/walking-god-of-karnataka-shivakumara-swamiji-passes-away/articleshow/67622412.cms |accessdate=21 January 2019 |work=The Times of India |date=21 January 2019}}</ref> He assumed charge of the Matha on 11 January 1941, following the death of Shivayogi Swami.<ref>{{cite news |title=Shivakumara Swami: timeline |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/karnataka/shivakumara-swami-timeline/article26058265.ece |newspaper=The Hindu |accessdate=22 January 2019 |language=en-IN |date=22 January 2019|last1=Bureau |first1=Karnataka }}</ref>\n\n==Social work==\nThe Swami founded a total of 132 institutions for education and training, that range from nursery to colleges for engineering, science, arts and management as well as vocational training.<ref name=\"TH_108Birthday\">{{cite news |last1=Bhuvaneshwari |first1=S. |title=108th birthday of Siddaganga mutt Seer celebrated |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/karnataka/108th-birthday-of-siddaganga-mutt-seer-celebrated/article7056938.ece |accessdate=21 January 2019 |publisher=The Hindu |date=1 April 2015 |language=en-IN}}</ref> He established educational institutions which offer courses in traditional learning of Sanskrit as well as modern science and technology. He was widely respected by all communities for his philanthropic work.<ref name=Siddaganga_Kalam>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindu.com/2006/04/08/stories/2006040810580500.htm|title=Kalam hails Siddaganga seer's contribution to society|accessdate=25 September 2009|location=Chennai, India|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|date=8 April 2006}}</ref>\n\nThe Swami's [[gurukula]] houses more than 10,000 children from ages five to sixteen years at any point in time and is open to children from all [[religion]]s, [[caste]]s, and [[creed]]s who are provided free food, education, and shelter (Trivida Dasohi).<ref name=\"TH_108Birthday\"/><ref name=\"firstpost21\">{{cite news |title=Shivakumara Swami's 111 years will be remembered as a life dedicated to simplicity, learning and service to society |url=https://www.firstpost.com/india/shivakumara-swamis-111-years-will-be-remembered-as-a-life-dedicated-to-simplicity-learning-and-service-to-society-5936501.html |accessdate=21 January 2019 |publisher=Firstpost |date=21 January 2019}}</ref> The pilgrims and visitors to the mutt also receive free meals.<ref name=\"TH_108Birthday\" /> Under the Swami's guidance, an annual agricultural fair is held for the benefit of the local population. The Government of Karnataka announced the institution of Shivakumara Swamiji Prashasti from 2007, the centennial birth anniversary of Swamiji.<ref name=Siddaganga_Kalam /> [[A. P. J. Abdul Kalam]], the former [[President of India]], visited him at Tumkur and praised the initiatives of Swami in education and humanitarian work.<ref name=Siddaganga_Kalam />\n\n==Illness and death==\nIn June 2016, Swami was hospitalised with jaundice and discharged later after treatment.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/bangalore/Siddaganga-seer-returns-to-Tumakuru/article14401332.ece|title=Siddaganga seer returns to Tumakuru|first=Staff|last=Correspondent|date=25 June 2016|publisher=|accessdate=21 January 2019|via=www.thehindu.com|newspaper=The Hindu}}</ref> He was again hospitalised in May 2017 and was diagnosed with various infections<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/bengaluru/siddaganga-mutt-seer-hospitalised/articleshow/58643314.cms|title=Siddaganga Mutt seer hospitalised|website=The Times of India}}</ref> but completely recovered after treatment. In September 2017, he was hospitalised again.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/states/karnataka/2017/sep/22/siddaganga-mutt-seer-hospitalised-in-kengeri-1660972.htmlSiddaganga|title=Mutt seer hospitalised in Kengeri|accessdate=30 December 2019}}</ref> In January 2018, he was diagnosed with pneumonia and a gallbladder infection, but made a full recovery after a brief hospitalisation.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/karnataka/siddaganga-seer-back-in-tumakuru-mutt/article22536214.ece|title=Siddaganga seer back in Tumakuru mutt|first=Staff|last=Reporter|date=27 January 2018|publisher=|accessdate=21 January 2019|via=www.thehindu.com|newspaper=The Hindu}}</ref> In June 2018, he was hospitalised again for a recurrence of the gallbladder infection.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/states/karnataka/2018/jun/22/siddaganga-seer-shivakumara-swami-hospitalised-discharged-later-1831889.html|title=Siddaganga seer Shivakumara Swami hospitalised, discharged later|website=The New Indian Express}}</ref> All of these treatments happened in BGS Hospital Bangalore and was treated by Dr. Ravindra B.S., chief of medical gastroenterology at the BGS Gleneagles Global Hospitals.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/karnataka/siddaganga-seer-to-be-shifted-to-chennai-hospital/article25683520.ece|title=Siddaganga seer to be shifted to Chennai hospital|last=|first=|date=7 December 2018|work=The Hindu|access-date=24 December 2019|url-status=live|others=Special Correspondent|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref>\n\nThe Swami returned to hospital on 1 December 2018, after suffering from a liver tube infection.<ref name=\"TH_Liverinfection\">{{cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/karnataka/siddaganga-seer-to-be-shifted-to-chennai-hospital/article25683520.ece|title=Siddaganga Mutt seer hospitalised|last=|first=|date=1 December 2018|work=|accessdate=21 January 2019|url-status=live|publisher=The Hindu|language=en-IN}}</ref> Although he was initially discharged, he was admitted again two days later. On 8 December, he underwent liver bypass and gallbladder removal surgeries, performed by [[Mohamed Rela]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/karnataka/siddaganga-seer-undergoes-surgery/article25697753.ece|title=Siddaganga seer undergoes surgery|date=8 December 2018|publisher=|accessdate=21 January 2019|via=www.thehindu.com|newspaper=The Hindu}}</ref> The surgeries were successful and the Swami was discharged after various days spent in the [[intensive care unit]]. On 29 December, he was diagnosed with a lung infection<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://publictv.in/siddaganga-sri-lung-infection-dr-parameshwar-tumkur/amp|title=\u0ca8\u0ca1\u0cc6\u0ca6\u0cbe\u0ca1\u0cc1\u0cb5 \u0ca6\u0cc7\u0cb5\u0cb0 \u0cb6\u0ccd\u0cb5\u0cbe\u0cb8\u0c95\u0ccb\u0cb6\u0ca6\u0cb2\u0ccd\u0cb2\u0cbf \u0cb8\u0ccb\u0c82\u0c95\u0cc1 \u0caa\u0ca4\u0ccd\u0ca4\u0cc6 - \u0cb6\u0ccd\u0cb0\u0cc0\u0c97\u0cb3 \u0c86\u0caa\u0ccd\u0ca4 \u0cb5\u0cc8\u0ca6\u0ccd\u0caf\u0cb0\u0cc1 \u0cb8\u0ccd\u0caa\u0cb7\u0ccd\u0c9f\u0ca8\u0cc6 - Public TV News|first=Public|last=TV|date=30 December 2018|accessdate=30 December 2019 |lang=kn}}</ref> and on 3 January 2019, he was hospitalised again.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/state/shivakumara-swami-shifted-711279.html|title=Shivakumara Swami shifted to hospital|date=3 January 2019|website=Deccan Herald|accessdate=21 January 2019}}</ref> On 11 January, he was placed on [[life support]] as his conditions deteriorated.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/state/siddaganga-seer-stay-712650.html|title=Siddaganga seer to stay on ventilator: Dr Manjunath|date=12 January 2019|website=Deccan Herald|accessdate=21 January 2019}}</ref> On 16 January, despite a complete lack of recovery, the Swami was shifted back to Siddaganga Matha as per his own will.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/karnataka/shivakumara-swami-shifted-to-siddaganga-mutt/article26001284.ece|title=Shivakumara Swami shifted to Siddaganga mutt|first=Staff|last=Reporter|date=16 January 2019|publisher=|accessdate=21 January 2019|via=www.thehindu.com|newspaper=The Hindu}}</ref> On 21 January, it was reported that he was in a critical condition after his pulse and blood pressure dropped. Attempts to revive him failed and he was pronounced dead at 11:44&nbsp;a.m. ([[Indian Standard Time|IST]]) that day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/bengaluru/live-updates-siddaganga-seer-critical-put-on-ventilator/liveblog/67619511.cms|title=Live updates: Siddaganga seer Shivakumara Swamiji critical, put on ventilator|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=21 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/shivakumara-swami-dead-1435579-2019-01-21|title=Lingayat seer Shivakumara Swami dies at 111, Karnataka declares 3-day state mourning|date=21 January 2019|location=Delhi|website=India Today}}</ref>\n[[File:The Prime Minister, Shri Narendra Modi meeting Sri Shivakumar Swamy ji, during his visit to the Siddaganga Mutt, at Tumkur, in Karnataka on September 24, 2014.jpg|thumb|Indian Prime Minister [[Narendra Modi]] with Swami in September 2014]] The [[Government of Karnataka]] declared a public holiday on 22 January as part of the three-day state mourning period in a mark of respect.<ref>{{cite news |title=Siddaganga Mutt seer death: Karnataka declares holiday tomorrow |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/kerala/siddaganga-mutt-seer-death-karnataka-declares-holiday-tomorrow/article26050521.ece |accessdate=21 January 2019 |work=The Hindu}}</ref>\n\n== Awards and recognitions ==\nIn recognition of his humanitarian work, the Swami was conferred with an honorary degree of [[Doctor of Letters|Doctor of Literature]] by the [[Karnataka University]] in 1965.<ref name=\"NDTV Walking God\">{{cite news |title=Shivakumara Swami, \"Walking God\", Dies At 111. Politicians Unite In Grief |url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/karnataka-seer-shivakumara-swami-who-was-on-ventilator-for-15-days-dies-at-111-1980835 |accessdate=21 January 2019 |publisher=NDTV.com |date=21 January 2019}}</ref> On his [[centenarian|centenary]] in 2007, the [[Government of Karnataka]] awarded Swami the prestigious [[Karnataka Ratna]] award, the highest civilian award of the state.<ref name=\"TNIE_110\">{{cite news |title=Seer turns 110, devotees seek Bharat Ratna |url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/states/karnataka/2017/apr/01/seer-turns-110-devotees-seek-bharat-ratna-1588518.html |accessdate=21 January 2019 |publisher=The New Indian Express |date=1 April 2017}}</ref> In 2015 the Government of India awarded him the [[Padma Bhushan]].<ref name=\"Hindu_passes\">{{cite news |last1=Bhuvaneshwari |first1=S. |title=Siddaganga Mutt head Shivakumara Swamy passes away |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/karnataka/siddaganga-mutt-seer-passes-away/article26049720.ece?homepage=true |accessdate=21 January 2019 |publisher=The Hindu |date=21 January 2019 |language=en-IN}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, the Government of Karnataka and his followers sought [[Bharat Ratna]] for him for his social service.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bharat Ratna sought for Siddaganga seer|url=http://www.hindu.com/2008/10/15/stories/2008101556060500.htm|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|date=15 October 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"TNIE_110\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Shivakumara Swami}}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20101011125007/http://archive.deccanherald.com/Deccanherald/Oct242006/spectrum14282320061023.asp A true Karma Yogi]\n* [http://www.sreesiddagangamutt.org Spiritual Holy Place - Sree Siddaganga Mutt]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{PadmaBhushanAwardRecipients 2010\u201319}}\n{{Karnataka topics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Swami, Shivakumara}}\n[[Category:20th-century Hindu religious leaders]]\n[[Category:21st-century Hindu religious leaders]]\n[[Category:Lingayatism]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Karnataka Ratna]]\n[[Category:1907 births]]\n[[Category:2019 deaths]]\n[[Category:Indian centenarians]]\n[[Category:Male supercentenarians]]\n[[Category:People from Tumkur district]]\n[[Category:Kannada people]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Padma Bhushan in other fields]]\n[[Category:Indian humanitarians]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indian saint}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Shivakumara Swami\n|image              = Shivakumara Swami.png\n|caption            = Shivakumara Swami in June 2007, aged 100\n|birth_name         = Shivanna\n|birth_date         = {{birth date|1907|4|1|df=y}}\n|birth_place        = Veerapura, [[Magadi]], [[Kingdom of Mysore]]<ref name=indianexpress-20190121>{{cite web |title=Who was Shivakumara Swami? |url=https://indianexpress.com/article/who-is/shivakumara-swami-lingayat-siddhaganga-mutt-tumakuru-5548096/ |website=The Indian Express |accessdate=21 January 2019 |language=en-IN |date=21 January 2019}}</ref>\n|death_date         = {{death date|2019|1|21|df=y}}<br/>(aged {{age in years and days|1907|4|1|2019|1|21}})<ref name=\"Hindu_passes\" />\n|death_place        = [[Tumkur]], Karnataka, India\n|other_names        = [[Siddaganga]] Swamigalu, Nadedaduva Devaru, Kayaka Yogi, Trivida Daasohi, Abhinava Basavanna<ref name=\"firstpost21\" />\n|organization       = Siddaganga Education Society\n|education          = [[Doctor of Literature]] (honourary, 1965)\n|occupation         = {{hlist|Humanitarian|spiritual leader|educator|head of [[Siddaganga Matha]]}} \n|awards             = [[Padma Bhushan]] (2015)<ref name=\"Hindu_passes\" /><br/>[[Karnataka Ratna]] (2007)<ref name=\"TNIE_110\" />\n|years_active       = 1930\u20132019\n}}\n\n'''Shivakumara Swami''' (born '''Shivanna'''; 1 April 1907 \u2013 21 January 2019) was an Indian [[supercentenarian]], humanitarian, spiritual leader and educator. He was a [[Lingayatism|Lingayat]] religious figure, he joined the [[Siddaganga Matha]] in 1930 [[Karnataka]] and became head seer from 1941.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sreesiddagangamutt.org/|title=Sree Siddaganga Mutt|website=Sreesiddagangamutt.org|accessdate=31 January 2018}}</ref> He also founded the Sri Siddaganga Education Society.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sit.ac.in|title=Siddaganga Institute of Technology|website=Sit.ac.in|accessdate=25 September 2009}}</ref> Described as the most esteemed adherent of [[Lingayatism]],<ref name=\"veconomist\">{{cite news|title=A medieval poet bedevils India's most powerful political party|url=https://www.economist.com/news/asia/21729449-did-he-found-faith-or-just-faction-medieval-poet-bedevils-indias-most-powerful-political|work=[[The Economist]]|date=21 September 2017}}</ref> he was referred to as ''Nadedaaduva Devaru'' (walking God) in the state.<ref name=\"Hindu_passes\" />\n\nBefore his death at the age of 111 years, 295 days, he was one of the oldest people [[India#Demographics|living in India]].<ref name=\"oldest_IT\">{{cite news |title=Lingayat seer Shivakumara Swami dies at 111, Karnataka declares 3-day state mourning |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/shivakumara-swami-dead-1435579-2019-01-21 |accessdate=21 January 2019 |publisher=India Today |date=21 January 2019 |language=en}}</ref> In 2015, he was awarded by the Government of India the [[Padma Bhushan]], India's third highest civilian award.<ref name=\"Hindu_passes\"/>\n\n==Early life==\nShivanna was born on 1 April 1907 in Veerapura, a village near [[Magadi]] in the erstwhile [[Kingdom of Mysore]] (in present-day [[Ramanagara district]] of [[Karnataka]] state). He was the youngest of thirteen children of Gangamma and Honne Gowda. Having been devoted followers of the deities Gangadhareshwara and Honnadevi, Shivanna's parents took him to the shrines in [[Shivagange]], alongside other religious centres around Veerapura.<ref>{{cite web |title=Childhood |url=http://www.siddagangamath.org/siddaganga/childhood.html |website=siddagangamath.org |accessdate=21 January 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190121135201/http://www.siddagangamath.org/siddaganga/childhood.html |archivedate=21 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Sri Shivakumara Swami: A proud Veerapura says adieu to its famous son |url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/states/karnataka/2019/jan/22/a-proud-veerapura-says-adieu-to-its-famous-son-1928296.html |website=The New Indian Express |accessdate=22 January 2019 |date=22 January 2019}}</ref> His mother Gangamma died when he was eight.<ref>{{cite news |title=Prominent Lingayat seer Shivakumara Swami dies at 111 |url=https://www.rediff.com/news/report/prominent-lingayat-seer-shivakumara-swami-dies-at-111/20190121.htm |accessdate=21 January 2019 |work=Rediff.com |date=21 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nShivanna completed his elementary education in a rural anglo-vernacular school in Nagavalli, a village in the present-day [[Tumkur district]]. He passed his matriculation in 1926. He was also a resident-student at the Siddaganga Math for a brief span during this time. He enrolled in [[Central College of Bangalore]] to study in arts with physics and mathematics as optional subjects,<ref>{{cite web |title=Education |url=http://www.siddagangamath.org/siddaganga/education.html |website=siddagangamath.org |accessdate=21 January 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180404103201/http://www.siddagangamath.org/siddaganga/education.html |archivedate=21 January 2019}}</ref> but was unable to earn the bachelor's degree as he was named successor of Uddana Shivayogi Swami to head the [[Siddaganga Matha]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bhuvaneshwari |first1=S. |title=Shivakumara Swami: the 'Walking God' who left no one behind |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/karnataka/shivakumara-swami-the-walking-god-who-left-no-one-behind/article26054420.ece |newspaper=The Hindu |accessdate=22 January 2019 |language=en-IN |date=21 January 2019}}</ref> Shivanna was proficient in [[Kannada]], [[Sanskrit]] and English languages.<ref name=\"TheWeek21Jan\">{{cite news |title=Shivakumara Swamiji: 'Walking god' who believed in the power of education |url=https://www.theweek.in/news/india/2019/01/21/shivakumara-swamiji-walking-god-believed0-power-education.html |accessdate=21 January 2019 |publisher=The Week |date=21 January 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nAfter losing his friend and the heir to head the Siddaganga Matha, Sri Marularadhya, in January 1930, Shivanna was chosen in his place by the incumbent chief Shivayogi Swami. Shivanna, then renamed Shivakumara, entered the ''viraktashram'' (the monks' order) on 3 March that year upon formal initiation, and assumed the pontifical name Shivakumara Swami.<ref>{{cite web |title=Shivanna to Sree Sivakumara Swamigalu |url=http://www.siddagangamath.org/siddaganga/destination.html |website=siddagangamath.org |accessdate=21 January 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190121135613/http://www.siddagangamath.org/siddaganga/destination.html |archivedate=21 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=B. R. |first1=Rohith |title=Shivakumara Swamiji, 'walking god' of Karnataka, passes away |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/bengaluru/walking-god-of-karnataka-shivakumara-swamiji-passes-away/articleshow/67622412.cms |accessdate=21 January 2019 |work=The Times of India |date=21 January 2019}}</ref> He assumed charge of the Matha on 11 January 1941, following the death of Shivayogi Swami.<ref>{{cite news |title=Shivakumara Swami: timeline |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/karnataka/shivakumara-swami-timeline/article26058265.ece |newspaper=The Hindu |accessdate=22 January 2019 |language=en-IN |date=22 January 2019|last1=Bureau |first1=Karnataka }}</ref>\n\n==Social work==\nThe Swami founded a total of 132 institutions for education and training, that range from nursery to colleges for engineering, science, arts and management as well as vocational training.<ref name=\"TH_108Birthday\">{{cite news |last1=Bhuvaneshwari |first1=S. |title=108th birthday of Siddaganga mutt Seer celebrated |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/karnataka/108th-birthday-of-siddaganga-mutt-seer-celebrated/article7056938.ece |accessdate=21 January 2019 |publisher=The Hindu |date=1 April 2015 |language=en-IN}}</ref> He established educational institutions which offer courses in traditional learning of Sanskrit as well as modern science and technology. He was widely respected by all communities for his philanthropic work.<ref name=Siddaganga_Kalam>{{cite news|url=http://www.hindu.com/2006/04/08/stories/2006040810580500.htm|title=Kalam hails Siddaganga seer's contribution to society|accessdate=25 September 2009|location=Chennai, India|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|date=8 April 2006}}</ref>\n\nThe Swami's [[gurukula]] houses more than 10,000 children from ages five to sixteen years at any point in time and is open to children from all [[religion]]s, [[caste]]s, and [[creed]]s who are provided free food, education, and shelter (Trivida Dasohi).<ref name=\"TH_108Birthday\"/><ref name=\"firstpost21\">{{cite news |title=Shivakumara Swami's 111 years will be remembered as a life dedicated to simplicity, learning and service to society |url=https://www.firstpost.com/india/shivakumara-swamis-111-years-will-be-remembered-as-a-life-dedicated-to-simplicity-learning-and-service-to-society-5936501.html |accessdate=21 January 2019 |publisher=Firstpost |date=21 January 2019}}</ref> The pilgrims and visitors to the mutt also receive free meals.<ref name=\"TH_108Birthday\" /> Under the Swami's guidance, an annual agricultural fair is held for the benefit of the local population. The Government of Karnataka announced the institution of Shivakumara Swamiji Prashasti from 2007, the centennial birth anniversary of Swamiji.<ref name=Siddaganga_Kalam /> [[A. P. J. Abdul Kalam]], the former [[President of India]], visited him at Tumkur and praised the initiatives of Swami in education and humanitarian work.<ref name=Siddaganga_Kalam />\n\n==Illness and death==\nIn June 2016, Swami was hospitalised with jaundice and discharged later after treatment.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/bangalore/Siddaganga-seer-returns-to-Tumakuru/article14401332.ece|title=Siddaganga seer returns to Tumakuru|first=Staff|last=Correspondent|date=25 June 2016|publisher=|accessdate=21 January 2019|via=www.thehindu.com|newspaper=The Hindu}}</ref> He was again hospitalised in May 2017 and was diagnosed with various infections<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/bengaluru/siddaganga-mutt-seer-hospitalised/articleshow/58643314.cms|title=Siddaganga Mutt seer hospitalised|website=The Times of India}}</ref> but completely recovered after treatment. In September 2017, he was hospitalised again.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/states/karnataka/2017/sep/22/siddaganga-mutt-seer-hospitalised-in-kengeri-1660972.htmlSiddaganga|title=Mutt seer hospitalised in Kengeri|accessdate=30 December 2019}}</ref> In January 2018, he was diagnosed with pneumonia and a gallbladder infection, but made a full recovery after a brief hospitalisation.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/karnataka/siddaganga-seer-back-in-tumakuru-mutt/article22536214.ece|title=Siddaganga seer back in Tumakuru mutt|first=Staff|last=Reporter|date=27 January 2018|publisher=|accessdate=21 January 2019|via=www.thehindu.com|newspaper=The Hindu}}</ref> In June 2018, he was hospitalised again for a recurrence of the gallbladder infection.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/states/karnataka/2018/jun/22/siddaganga-seer-shivakumara-swami-hospitalised-discharged-later-1831889.html|title=Siddaganga seer Shivakumara Swami hospitalised, discharged later|website=The New Indian Express}}</ref> All of these treatments happened in BGS Hospital Bangalore and was treated by Dr. Ravindra B.S., chief of medical gastroenterology at the BGS Gleneagles Global Hospitals.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/karnataka/siddaganga-seer-to-be-shifted-to-chennai-hospital/article25683520.ece|title=Siddaganga seer to be shifted to Chennai hospital|last=|first=|date=7 December 2018|work=The Hindu|access-date=24 December 2019|url-status=live|others=Special Correspondent|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref>\n\nThe Swami returned to hospital on 1 December 2018, after suffering from a liver tube infection.<ref name=\"TH_Liverinfection\">{{cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/karnataka/siddaganga-seer-to-be-shifted-to-chennai-hospital/article25683520.ece|title=Siddaganga Mutt seer hospitalised|last=|first=|date=1 December 2018|work=|accessdate=21 January 2019|url-status=live|publisher=The Hindu|language=en-IN}}</ref> Although he was initially discharged, he was admitted again two days later. On 8 December, he underwent liver bypass and gallbladder removal surgeries, performed by [[Mohamed Rela]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/karnataka/siddaganga-seer-undergoes-surgery/article25697753.ece|title=Siddaganga seer undergoes surgery|date=8 December 2018|publisher=|accessdate=21 January 2019|via=www.thehindu.com|newspaper=The Hindu}}</ref> The surgeries were successful and the Swami was discharged after various days spent in the [[intensive care unit]]. On 29 December, he was diagnosed with a lung infection<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://publictv.in/siddaganga-sri-lung-infection-dr-parameshwar-tumkur/amp|title=\u0ca8\u0ca1\u0cc6\u0ca6\u0cbe\u0ca1\u0cc1\u0cb5 \u0ca6\u0cc7\u0cb5\u0cb0 \u0cb6\u0ccd\u0cb5\u0cbe\u0cb8\u0c95\u0ccb\u0cb6\u0ca6\u0cb2\u0ccd\u0cb2\u0cbf \u0cb8\u0ccb\u0c82\u0c95\u0cc1 \u0caa\u0ca4\u0ccd\u0ca4\u0cc6 - \u0cb6\u0ccd\u0cb0\u0cc0\u0c97\u0cb3 \u0c86\u0caa\u0ccd\u0ca4 \u0cb5\u0cc8\u0ca6\u0ccd\u0caf\u0cb0\u0cc1 \u0cb8\u0ccd\u0caa\u0cb7\u0ccd\u0c9f\u0ca8\u0cc6 - Public TV News|first=Public|last=TV|date=30 December 2018|accessdate=30 December 2019 |lang=kn}}</ref> and on 3 January 2019, he was hospitalised again.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/state/shivakumara-swami-shifted-711279.html|title=Shivakumara Swami shifted to hospital|date=3 January 2019|website=Deccan Herald|accessdate=21 January 2019}}</ref> On 11 January, he was placed on [[life support]] as his conditions deteriorated.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.deccanherald.com/state/siddaganga-seer-stay-712650.html|title=Siddaganga seer to stay on ventilator: Dr Manjunath|date=12 January 2019|website=Deccan Herald|accessdate=21 January 2019}}</ref> On 16 January, despite a complete lack of recovery, the Swami was shifted back to Siddaganga Matha as per his own will.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/karnataka/shivakumara-swami-shifted-to-siddaganga-mutt/article26001284.ece|title=Shivakumara Swami shifted to Siddaganga mutt|first=Staff|last=Reporter|date=16 January 2019|publisher=|accessdate=21 January 2019|via=www.thehindu.com|newspaper=The Hindu}}</ref> On 21 January, it was reported that he was in a critical condition after his pulse and blood pressure dropped. Attempts to revive him failed and he was pronounced dead at 11:44&nbsp;a.m. ([[Indian Standard Time|IST]]) that day.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/bengaluru/live-updates-siddaganga-seer-critical-put-on-ventilator/liveblog/67619511.cms|title=Live updates: Siddaganga seer Shivakumara Swamiji critical, put on ventilator|website=The Times of India|language=en|access-date=21 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/shivakumara-swami-dead-1435579-2019-01-21|title=Lingayat seer Shivakumara Swami dies at 111, Karnataka declares 3-day state mourning|date=21 January 2019|location=Delhi|website=India Today}}</ref>\n[[File:The Prime Minister, Shri Narendra Modi meeting Sri Shivakumar Swamy ji, during his visit to the Siddaganga Mutt, at Tumkur, in Karnataka on September 24, 2014.jpg|thumb|Indian Prime Minister [[Narendra Modi]] with Swami in September 2014]] The [[Government of Karnataka]] declared a public holiday on 22 January as part of the three-day state mourning period in a mark of respect.<ref>{{cite news |title=Siddaganga Mutt seer death: Karnataka declares holiday tomorrow |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/kerala/siddaganga-mutt-seer-death-karnataka-declares-holiday-tomorrow/article26050521.ece |accessdate=21 January 2019 |work=The Hindu}}</ref>\n\n== Awards and recognitions ==\nIn recognition of his humanitarian work, the Swami was conferred with an honorary degree of [[Doctor of Letters|Doctor of Literature]] by the [[Karnataka University]] in 1965.<ref name=\"NDTV Walking God\">{{cite news |title=Shivakumara Swami, \"Walking God\", Dies At 111. Politicians Unite In Grief |url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/karnataka-seer-shivakumara-swami-who-was-on-ventilator-for-15-days-dies-at-111-1980835 |accessdate=21 January 2019 |publisher=NDTV.com |date=21 January 2019}}</ref> On his [[centenarian|centenary]] in 2007, the [[Government of Karnataka]] awarded Swami the prestigious [[Karnataka Ratna]] award, the highest civilian award of the state.<ref name=\"TNIE_110\">{{cite news |title=Seer turns 110, devotees seek Bharat Ratna |url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/states/karnataka/2017/apr/01/seer-turns-110-devotees-seek-bharat-ratna-1588518.html |accessdate=21 January 2019 |publisher=The New Indian Express |date=1 April 2017}}</ref> In 2015 the Government of India awarded him the [[Padma Bhushan]].<ref name=\"Hindu_passes\">{{cite news |last1=Bhuvaneshwari |first1=S. |title=Siddaganga Mutt head Shivakumara Swamy passes away |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/karnataka/siddaganga-mutt-seer-passes-away/article26049720.ece?homepage=true |accessdate=21 January 2019 |publisher=The Hindu |date=21 January 2019 |language=en-IN}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, the Government of Karnataka and his followers sought [[Bharat Ratna]] for him for his social service.<ref>{{cite news|title=Bharat Ratna sought for Siddaganga seer|url=http://www.hindu.com/2008/10/15/stories/2008101556060500.htm|newspaper=[[The Hindu]]|date=15 October 2008}}</ref><ref name=\"TNIE_110\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Shivakumara Swami}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20101011125007/http://archive.deccanherald.com/Deccanherald/Oct242006/spectrum14282320061023.asp A true Karma Yogi]\n*[http://www.sreesiddagangamutt.org Spiritual Holy Place - Sree Siddaganga Mutt]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{PadmaBhushanAwardRecipients 2010\u201319}}\n{{Karnataka topics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Swami, Shivakumara}}\n[[Category:20th-century Hindu religious leaders]]\n[[Category:21st-century Hindu religious leaders]]\n[[Category:Lingayatism]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Karnataka Ratna]]\n[[Category:1907 births]]\n[[Category:2019 deaths]]\n[[Category:Indian centenarians]]\n[[Category:Male supercentenarians]]\n[[Category:People from Tumkur district]]\n[[Category:Kannada people]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Padma Bhushan in other fields]]\n[[Category:Indian humanitarians]]\n", "name_user": "GiantSnowman", "label": "safe", "comment": "date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript| Cleaned up usingAutoEd", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shivakumara_Swami"}
{"title_page": "Deaths in 2020", "text_new": "{{pp-vandalism|small=yes}}\n{{Short description|List of notable individuals who died in 2020}}\nThe following deaths of notable individuals occurred in 2020. Names are reported under the date of death, in alphabetical order by surname or pseudonym.\n\nA typical entry reports information in the following sequence:\n\n* Name, age, country of citizenship at birth, subsequent [[nationality]] (if applicable), what subject was noted for, cause of death (if known), and reference.\n\n<!--\n* * * * * * * Please adhere to the guidelines below when adding a name to this article. * * * * * * *\n\nA typical entry reports information in the following sequence: Name, age, country of citizenship at birth or nationality if the subject is not eligible (for example, in the case of animals), subsequent nationality (if applicable), what subject was noted for, cause of death (if known), and reference. Do not place a period at the end of the entry. Names are reported under the date of death. Names under each date are reported in alphabetical order by surname or pseudonym.\n\n(1) Please add only those meeting Wikipedia notability guidelines. Include a reference to a reliable source.[a] [b] If a Wikipedia article for the dead does not yet exist, reconsider whether the subject is actually notable. If so, consider writing an article yourself. Those without a Wikipedia article are removed after one month.\n\n(2) Please understand that the intent of this article is to report notable deaths. Tragic deaths, while unfortunate, do not necessarily render the dead \"notable\". If you report the death of a notable subject that does not already have a Wikipedia article, consider starting one. Include third-party sources other than the obituary.\n\n(3) Please add entries in alphabetical order by family name. Please avoid over-linking. As such, please do not add links to nationalities, common occupations, or common causes of death. Rather, include only \"links that aid navigation and understanding\". Thank you.\n\n(4) References should be in <ref>[url & title]</ref> format, as full citations make the page too slow to load, and too big to edit.\n\n--Notes--\n[a] See [[WP:RS]] for definition of reliable source, and [[WP:BLPSOURCE]] for living and recently deceased persons.\n[b] For information on using information from Ancestry.com, Find-a-grave, or IMDb, please see [[WP:ELPEREN]].\n* * * * * * * Please adhere to the guidelines above when adding a name to this article. * * * * * * *\n\n--->\n{{TOC right}}\n\n==April==\n===2===\n\n===1===\n*[[Nur Hassan Hussein]], 83, Somali politician, [[List of prime ministers of Somalia|Prime Minister]] (2007\u20132009) and Ambassador to Italy (since 2009), [[COVID-19]].<ref>[https://www.garoweonline.com/en/news/somalia/ex-somali-pm-dies-of-coronavirus-in-london Ex-Somali PM dies of Coronavirus in London]</ref>\n*[[Martin Khor]], 68, Malaysian journalist (''[[The Star (Malaysia)|The Star]]'') and economist, executive director of the [[South Centre (organization)|South Centre]] (2009\u20132018), cancer.<ref>[https://www.thestar.com.my/news/nation/2020/04/01/former-third-world-network-director-martin-khor-dies-of-cancer Former Third World Network director Martin Khor dies of cancer]</ref>\n\n==March==\n===31===\n*[[Pierre B\u00e9nichou]], 82, Algerian-born French journalist.<ref>[https://www.lemonde.fr/disparitions/article/2020/03/31/mort-de-pierre-benichou-ancien-dirigeant-de-l-obs-et-chroniqueur-des-grosses-tetes_6035051_3382.html Mort de Pierre B\u00e9nichou, ancien dirigeant de \u00ab L\u2019Obs \u00bb et chroniqueur des \u00ab Grosses T\u00eates \u00bb] {{in lang|fr}}</ref>\n*{{ill|Rafael Berrio|es}}, 56, Spanish composer and singer.<ref>[https://www.diariovasco.com/culturas/musica/rafa-berrio-fallece-musico-donostiarra-20200331185524-nt.html Fallece Rafael Berrio, gran poeta, bohemio, y rockero del 'underground' donostiarra] {{in lang|es}}</ref>\n*[[Michel Chodkiewicz]], 90,  French